CA123643&13961&376069&0.0&evidence&11681&https://civicdb.org/links/evidence/11681&35363510_(PUBMED)&SOMATIC&accepted&SENSITIVITYRESPONSE&DOES_NOT_SUPPORT&Cancer&Selumetinib_(NCIt_ID_C66939)&&&B&3&&&&&&T&Missense_Variant&BRAF&673&transcript&ENST00000288602.6&ENST00000288602.6:c.1799T>A&&V600E&12&RS113488022&VAL600GLU&V640E&VAL640GLU&https://civicdb.org/links/variants/12&BRAF_V600E_OR_NRAS_Mutation_OR_HRAS_Mutation_OR_KRAS_Mutation_OR_NF1_Inactivating_Mutation&4748&&https://civicdb.org/links/molecular-profiles/4748&NM_004333.4:c.1799T>A&NP_004324.2:p.Val600Glu&NC_000007.13:g.140453136A>T&ENST00000288602.6:c.1799T>A&CA123643&13961&376069&0.0&evidence&11696&https://civicdb.org/links/evidence/11696&35363510_(PUBMED)&SOMATIC&accepted&SENSITIVITYRESPONSE&DOES_NOT_SUPPORT&Cancer&Selumetinib_(NCIt_ID_C66939)&&&B&3&&&&&&T&Missense_Variant&BRAF&673&transcript&ENST00000288602.6&ENST00000288602.6:c.1799T>A&&V600E&12&RS113488022&VAL600GLU&V640E&VAL640GLU&https://civicdb.org/links/variants/12&BRAF_V600E_AND_NF1_Loss&5379&&https://civicdb.org/links/molecular-profiles/5379&NM_004333.4:c.1799T>A&NP_004324.2:p.Val600Glu&NC_000007.13:g.140453136A>T&ENST00000288602.6:c.1799T>A&CA123643&13961&376069&0.0&evidence&90&https://civicdb.org/links/evidence/90&24576830_(PUBMED)&SOMATIC&accepted&RESISTANCE&SUPPORTS&Melanoma&Vemurafenib_(NCIt_ID_C64768)&&&D&3&&&&&&T&Missense_Variant&BRAF&673&transcript&ENST00000288602.6&ENST00000288602.6:c.1799T>A&&V600E&12&RS113488022&VAL600GLU&V640E&VAL640GLU&https://civicdb.org/links/variants/12&BRAF_V600E_AND_GNAS_R201C&5491&&https://civicdb.org/links/molecular-profiles/5491&NM_004333.4:c.1799T>A&NP_004324.2:p.Val600Glu&NC_000007.13:g.140453136A>T&ENST00000288602.6:c.1799T>A&CA123643&13961&376069&0.0&evidence&1906&https://civicdb.org/links/evidence/1906&27729313_(PUBMED)&SOMATIC&accepted&RESISTANCE&SUPPORTS&Colorectal_Cancer&Cetuximab_(NCIt_ID_C1723)&Irinotecan_(NCIt_ID_C62040)&Vemurafenib_(NCIt_ID_C64768)&COMBINATION&&C&2&&&&&&T&Missense_Variant&BRAF&673&transcript&ENST00000288602.6&ENST00000288602.6:c.1799T>A&&V600E&12&RS113488022&VAL600GLU&V640E&VAL640GLU&https://civicdb.org/links/variants/12&BRAF_V600E_AND_ARAF_S490T&5492&&https://civicdb.org/links/molecular-profiles/5492&NM_004333.4:c.1799T>A&NP_004324.2:p.Val600Glu&NC_000007.13:g.140453136A>T&ENST00000288602.6:c.1799T>A&CA123643&13961&376069&0.0&evidence&1905&https://civicdb.org/links/evidence/1905&27729313_(PUBMED)&SOMATIC&accepted&RESISTANCE&SUPPORTS&Colorectal_Cancer&Cetuximab_(NCIt_ID_C1723)&Irinotecan_(NCIt_ID_C62040)&Vemurafenib_(NCIt_ID_C64768)&COMBINATION&&C&1&&&&&	chr7:140753336-140753336				1	BRAF	p.V600E				500	0.99	240	True	v6.2	[]	Gain-of-function	The class I activating exon 15 BRAF V600E mutation is located in the kinase domain of the BRAF protein and is highly recurrent in melanoma, lung and thyroid cancer, among others (PMID: 28783719, 26091043, 25079552, 23833300, 25417114, 28783719, 12068308). This mutation has been comprehensively biologically characterized and has been shown to activate the downstream MAPK pathway independent of RAS (PMID: 15035987, 12068308, 19251651, 26343582), to render BRAF constitutively activated in monomeric form (PMID: 20179705), and to retain sensitivity to RAF monomer inhibitors such as vemurafenib and dabrafenib (PMID:26343582, 28783719, 20179705, 30351999).	True	BRAF, an intracellular kinase, is frequently mutated in melanoma, thyroid and lung cancers among others.	True	11/01/2023	Oncogenic	25417114|20179705|23833300|26091043|26343582|12068308|30351999|25079552|28783719|19251651|15035987	[]	V600E	673	BRAF	GRCh38	UNKNOWN	MUTATION	[]	While the RAF-inhibitor dabrafenib in combination with the MEK1/2-targeted inhibitor trametinib is FDA-approved for the treatment of patients with BRAF V600E mutant solid tumors, the clinical utility of dabrafenib in combination with trametinib in patients with BRAF V600E mutant UNKNOWN has yet to be defined.	True	The BRAF V600E mutation is known to be oncogenic.	False	chr7	140453136	140753336	True	True	True	Oncogenic						[]	[]	False	True		BRAF, an intracellular kinase, is frequently mutated in melanoma, thyroid and lung cancers among others.	The BRAF V600E mutation is known to be oncogenic.	While the RAF-inhibitor dabrafenib in combination with the MEK1/2-targeted inhibitor trametinib is FDA-approved for the treatment of patients with BRAF V600E mutant solid tumors, the clinical utility of dabrafenib in combination with trametinib in patients with BRAF V600E mutant UNKNOWN has yet to be defined.			[]	[]	[]	v6.2	11/01/2023		GRCh38	BRAF	673	V600E			UNKNOWN							Gain-of-function	The class I activating exon 15 BRAF V600E mutation is located in the kinase domain of the BRAF protein and is highly recurrent in melanoma, lung and thyroid cancer, among others (PMID: 28783719, 26091043, 25079552, 23833300, 25417114, 28783719, 12068308). This mutation has been comprehensively biologically characterized and has been shown to activate the downstream MAPK pathway independent of RAS (PMID: 15035987, 12068308, 19251651, 26343582), to render BRAF constitutively activated in monomeric form (PMID: 20179705), and to retain sensitivity to RAF monomer inhibitors such as vemurafenib and dabrafenib (PMID:26343582, 28783719, 20179705, 30351999).	['25417114', '20179705', '23833300', '26091043', '26343582', '12068308', '30351999', '25079552', '28783719', '19251651', '15035987']	[]	{"query":{"id":null,"referenceGenome":"GRCh38","hugoSymbol":"BRAF","entrezGeneId":673,"alteration":"V600E","alterationType":null,"svType":null,"tumorType":"UNKNOWN","consequence":null,"proteinStart":null,"proteinEnd":null,"hgvs":null,"hgvsInfo":null,"canonicalTranscript":null},"geneExist":true,"variantExist":true,"alleleExist":true,"oncogenic":"Oncogenic","mutationEffect":{"knownEffect":"Gain-of-function","description":"The class I activating exon 15 BRAF V600E mutation is located in the kinase domain of the BRAF protein and is highly recurrent in melanoma, lung and thyroid cancer, among others (PMID: 28783719, 26091043, 25079552, 23833300, 25417114, 28783719, 12068308). This mutation has been comprehensively biologically characterized and has been shown to activate the downstream MAPK pathway independent of RAS (PMID: 15035987, 12068308, 19251651, 26343582), to render BRAF constitutively activated in monomeric form (PMID: 20179705), and to retain sensitivity to RAF monomer inhibitors such as vemurafenib and dabrafenib (PMID:26343582, 28783719, 20179705, 30351999).","citations":{"pmids":["25417114","20179705","23833300","26091043","26343582","12068308","30351999","25079552","28783719","19251651","15035987"],"abstracts":[]}},"highestSensitiveLevel":null,"highestResistanceLevel":null,"highestDiagnosticImplicationLevel":null,"highestPrognosticImplicationLevel":null,"highestFdaLevel":null,"otherSignificantSensitiveLevels":[],"otherSignificantResistanceLevels":[],"VUS":false,"hotspot":true,"exon":null,"geneSummary":"BRAF, an intracellular kinase, is frequently mutated in melanoma, thyroid and lung cancers among others.","variantSummary":"The BRAF V600E mutation is known to be oncogenic.","tumorTypeSummary":"While the RAF-inhibitor dabrafenib in combination with the MEK1/2-targeted inhibitor trametinib is FDA-approved for the treatment of patients with BRAF V600E mutant solid tumors, the clinical utility of dabrafenib in combination with trametinib in patients with BRAF V600E mutant UNKNOWN has yet to be defined.","prognosticSummary":"","diagnosticSummary":"","diagnosticImplications":[],"prognosticImplications":[],"treatments":[],"dataVersion":"v6.2","lastUpdate":"11/01/2023"}	True	True	True	Gain-of-function	25417114;20179705;23833300;26091043;26343582;12068308;30351999;25079552;28783719;19251651;15035987	Oncogenic	Dabrafenib,Dabrafenib+Trametinib,Encorafenib+Binimetinib,Encorafenib+Cetuximab,Encorafenib+Cetuximab+FOLFOX Regimen,Tovorafenib,Trametinib,Vemurafenib,Vemurafenib+Atezolizumab+Cobimetinib,Vemurafenib+Cobimetinib	Encorafenib+Panitumumab,Selumetinib,Vemur